Excel 4.0

PROBLEM: Changing your data to create what-if scenarios destroys your
valid data.

SOLUTION: Keep old worksheet data for later comparison by moving the
original values to a macro sheet out of harm's way. To copy a range named
InputValues to the name OldValues on the macro sheet, use the statement:

=SET.NAME("OldValues",DEREF(!InputValues))

The DEREF function forces Excel to assign the values from the reference
to the name, rather than assigning a pointer to the reference. Because
InputValues refers to a whole array of names, you must use
Ctrl-Shift-Enter to enter the SET.NAME function so that Excel interprets
the array properly. (After you run the macro, use Formula Define Name to
look at the name OldValues.) You can also put the original values back
onto the worksheet with the RestoreValues macro:

RestoreValues

=SELECT(!InputValues)

=FORMULA.ARRAY(OldValues)

=COPY()

=PASTE.SPECIAL(3)

=CANCEL.COPY()

=RETURN()

Be sure to use Ctrl-Shift-Enter when you enter the FORMULA.ARRAY
statement.

